questions.answer: Each head of federal power should be interpreted simply on the words of the grant; Commonwealth legislation under s 51(xxxv) (conciliation and arbitration) can bind the States in their exercise of residual powers (nothing limits the natural extent of the power because no reserved State power); an award of the Commonwealth Court of Conciliation and Arbitration binds a State government in its capacity as an employer (no immunity)

questions.question: APLA Limited v Legal Services Commissioner (NSW) (2005) 224 CLR 322
questions.mnemonic: [Apple a] day keeps the doctor away so no personal injury
questions.answer:
NSW prohibited lawyer advertising re personal injury claims
 plaintiffs argued inconsistent with Trade Practices Act (Cth) (which included provisions to protect certain people who are injured by faulty goods) because can’t exercise those rights without access to a lawyer
(1) inconsistency? majority: State legislation did not impair the functioning of the Trade Practices Act or other federal legislation (could still access a lawyer);  Gummow J: (obiter) in some cases a State law restricting access to legal counsel might impair Cth law (for the purposes of s109) legislation such as the Trade Practices Act and
(2) judicial power? the Judiciary Act that provide the mechanisms for the exercise of federal judicial power
(3) s92 free trade/intercourse? Gummow J: 'the question becomes one whether the impediment imposed on that intercourse is greater than that reasonably required to achieve the objects of the legislation' = valid 
Callinan J: nothing in the law prevented provision of legal services or free passage of lawyers = within what was reasonably required to implement the object of the legislation

questions.question: Clyde Engineering Co Ltd v Cowburn (1926)
questions.mnemonic: Commonwealth award and State working hours [collide]
questions.answer: The Forty-Four Hours Week Act 1925 (NSW) provided that workers under a Commonwealth award which stipulated a working week longer than 44 hours should be paid their full wages if they had worked for 44 hours. However, the Commonwealth award stated that a worker who performed less than 48 hours of work should have pay deducted for non-attendance. Isaacs J established the 'cover the field' test for inconsistency between a Commonwealth and a State law. Not direct inconsistency because State could deduct and refund to get around the award.

questions.question: Victoria v Commonwealth ('PMA Case') (1975) 134 CLR 81
questions.mnemonic: Post-Mortem Analysis of dead deadlocked bill's passage
questions.answer: Invaldated Act to establish a Petroleum and Minerals Authority to explore and sell petroleum because non-compliant with deadlock provision (s 57): last sitting day of the year (13 Dec 1973), Senate received PMA Bill: Senate passed motion that the debate be adjourned until first sitting day in Feb 1974; After debate, Senate on 2 April 1974, rejected the Bill; 8 April 1974 [i.e. not 3 months from 2 April], House of Representatives again passed the Bill; 10 April: Senate resolved that the Bill be deferred ‘till this day six months’; double dissolution election on 11 April 1974, in purported pursuance of s 57 (other earlier bills too, see below); Bill passed by the House of Representatives on 11 July 1974, rejected by Senate; joint sitting of both Houses convened 6 August 1974, affirmed by an absolute majority, GG declared assent; Issues: (1) Whether Senate had 'failed to pass' the Bill on 13 December, and (2) if not, could court strike law down on this basis? Barwick CJ: High Court is the guardian of the Constitution: dismissed argument that the terms of s 57 were directory rather than mandatory; if the joint sitting were not authorized by law (i.e. pursuant to the constitutional powers of the Governor General), a law passed by that joint sitting would be invalid; Senate no mere ‘house of review’, and as evident from the provisions of section 53-55, was essentially the equal of the House of Representatives. Therefore requires opportunity to properly consider a bill; would have to be demonstrated that the Senate was merely prevaricating before a delay could be considered 'failing to pass' the bill; the conduct of the Senate has to be considered on a case-by-case basis; referring a bill to a select committee might be considered 'failing to pass' in certain circumstances; on these facts, adjourning consideration until the next day of sitting (albeit after Christmas) was not prevarication and was not there for a failure to pass.

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: W & G McArthur Ltd v Queensland (1920) 28 CLR 530
questions.mnemonic: John Macarthur a jack of all trades
questions.answer:
everyday usage' informs the scope of the power in section 51(i) (no special ‘legal’ meaning)
includes (at its core) negotiations, bargaining, transport and delivery relating to the exchange of goods, etc.

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Australian National Airways v Commonwealth (1945) 71 CLR 29
questions.mnemonic: Airways big business after the war
questions.answer:
Held: transport (of people) could be considered 'trade and commerce'
Dixon J: ‘It is a constitution that we are interpreting, an instrument of government meant to endure and conferring powers expressed in general propositions wide enough to be capable of flexible application to changing circumstances.’ 
=Flexible, broad interpretation

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Bank of New South Wales v The Commonwealth (1948) 76 CLR (the Bank Nationalisation Case)
questions.mnemonic: Banks the epitome of free trade; shareholders proprietors
questions.answer:
Chifley Labor government tried to nationalise the banks (remove from private hands) 
included ban on private banks;Commonwealth legislative scheme to transfer the business of private banks to a public national ‘Commonwealth bank’
allowed Commonwealth Government to buy shares and assets of the private banks (i.e. with compensation) and replace directors of the private bank boards
Dixon J (majority): 
(1) trade and commerce power not to be interpreted narrowly
includes supply of electricity or gas, and communication such as media broadcasting and banking  (not just tangible things)
even if not conducted to obtain a profit
(2) ban on banks invalid because it breached s 92 (‘trade, commerce, and intercourse among the States, … shall be absolutely free’) 
(3)(and s 51(xxxi) appropriation without just terms) (Dixon J): proprietary rights not just title to property. The bundle of rights includes control/substance etc. that sits under the title 
=so there can be an acquisition even if title remains in hand of shareholders because the law removed effective control over their property

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Re The Maritime Union of Australia; Ex parte CSL Pacific Shipping Inc (2003) 214 CLR 397
questions.mnemonic: [See us, el] amigo, say foreign crews to unions
questions.answer:
Australian Industrial Relations Commission tried to exercise jurisdiction over workplace relations over foreign workers on a foreign ship by a foreign company:
Held: 
sufficient connection: 'a ship journeying for reward is in commerce. Those who co-operate in the journeying of the ship are in commerce and the wages of those persons and the conditions of their employment relate to that commerce.’
sufficient connection to trade and commerce power while the ship is trading in Australian waters or on a voyage to or from an Australian port

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Murphyores Inc Pty Ltd v Commonwealth (1976) 136 CLR 1
questions.mnemonic: Trade licence on [murphy, or] environmental furphy
questions.answer: Commonwealth able to make regulations imposing licences and licence conditions (e.g. environmental conditions) under the trade and commerce power because the product was being exported

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Pape v The Commissioner of Taxation (2009) 238 CLR 1
questions.mnemonic: Party pooper Pape
questions.answer:
spending 'tax bonus' to combat GFC
(1) nationhood power;‘…short-term fiscal measures to meet adverse economic conditions affecting the nation as a whole, where such measures are on their face peculiarly within the capacity and resources of the Commonwealth Government’ (French CJ); 
nationhood power from s61 (and s51(xxxix), not implied
Gummow, Crennan and Bell J: ‘The Executive Government is the arm of government capable of and empowered to respond to a crisis be it war, natural disaster or a financial crisis on the scale here’
Heydon J (dissent): executive power does not extend beyond the Parliament's legislative competence codified through the heads of power in s 51 
(2) majority did not consider s 51(i), but dissenting judges: appropriation of money designed to stimulate the national economy did not have sufficient connection to international or interstate trade and commerce (despite argument that the cash injection was designed to stimulate national and international trade)

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Minister for Justice (WA) (Ex rel Ansett Transport Industries (Operations) Pty Ltd v Australian National Airlines Commission  ("Western Australia Airlines case" ) (1976) 138 CLR 492
questions.mnemonic: [And set] the flight path over the border or else
questions.answer:
Commonwealth body (Australian National Airlines Commission ) provided airline services under Act
flew from Perth to Darwin, but stopped at a destination within Western Australia (Port Hedland)
majority: intrastate leg of journey invalid, even if ultimate destination to a Territory or to another State
cited Redfern v Dunlop Rubber Australia Pty Ltd (1964) 110 CLR 194
for there to be a sufficient connection, the intrastate and interstate trade must be 'inseparably connected', not merely in a relationship of economic cause and effect
upshot: Commonwealth unable to use trade and commerce power to extend national regulation over airlines and comparable industries

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Airlines of New South Wales (No. 2) (1965) 113 CLR 54
questions.mnemonic: State water different quality? So is air
questions.answer:
(1) inconsistency point: considered to what degree the States can regulate air safety in the face of federal attempts to regulate the field
held: no inconsistency under s 109 (see inconsistency slides: separate areas (State: navigation within a State and pilots, federal: Cth airports, safety, and efficiency)
(2) characterisation point: rejected any argument that the 'field' of air navigation was so intermingled (i.e. it is all the same air space) so as to permit regulation of (purely) intrastate navigation under the trade and commerce power

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Granall v Marrickville Margarine Pty Ltd (1955) 93 CLR 55
questions.mnemonic: [Grain all] affected whether in factory or the farm, same with margarine
questions.answer:
(1) manufacturing is not 'trade', but there may be occasions when the incidental aspect of the trade and commerce power reaches into those activities that occur in 'the factory or the farm', as opposed to transit and exchange
(section 51(xxxix) and implied into each enumerated power)

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: O'Sullivan v Noarlunga Meat Ltd (1954) 92 CLR 565
questions.mnemonic: [Sully van no longer], regulate the abbatoir
questions.answer:
whether the Commonwealth could regulate practices in an abattoir for quality
Fullagar J (majority): ‘packing, get-up, description, labelling, handling, and anything at all that may reasonably be considered likely to affect an export market by developing it or impairing it.’
‘the objectives for which the power is conferred may be impossible of achievement by means of a mere prescription of standards …[it] may very reasonably be thought necessary to go further back, and even to enter the factory or the field or the mine.’
‘depend[s] on the particular circumstances attending the production or manufacture of particular commodities'
Note: incidental power used to regulate activity that was both preparatory to trade and commerce, and occurring purely within the borders of one State (despite the terms of s51(i): 'among the States‘) 
McTiernan J: also substantial connection with the ‘core’ power (i.e. didn’t need to invoke incidental power)

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Air Services Australia v Canadian Airlines (1999) 202 CLR 133
questions.mnemonic: Everybody secure your luggage or incident of leaking maple syrup
questions.answer:
Commonwealth 'lien' (a security interest to ensure payment) on aircraft for administration and regulation of air safety, traffic control
Held: (1) fee for service rather than tax 
relationship between the fee and the services need not necessarily be a direct relationship (i.e. where the fee paid by one recipient of the service is calculated according to the cost of providing the service to that particular individual)
(2) incidental to trade and commerce power

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: R v Trade Practices Tribunal; Ex parte St George County Council (1974) 130 CLR 533
questions.mnemonic: St George, the council, not the business
questions.answer:
an incorporated local council not a financial corporation or trading corporation even though it engaged in trading activities because the purpose of the council was to serve the public interest 
obiter dicta: same for universities, churches, public utilities (for water and sewerage), etc.

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: R v Judges of the Federal Court of Australia; ex parte Western Australian National Football League (Adamson's case) (1979) 143 CLR 190
questions.mnemonic: [A damn son] leaving our club team for another
questions.answer:
Brian Adamson wanted to transfer to a SA AFL football club from a WA one; Club rules prevented; whether the competition provisions of the Commonwealth Trade Practices Act applied to the football club in question (yes)
majority: if a sporting club was engaging in activities that gained income (e.g. selling tickets, merchandise, etc.) that club may be regarded as a trading corporation
Matter of degree: 
some charity-oriented commerce incidental to main activity of trade = trading corp
some commerce merely incidental to main activity charity = not trading corp

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: State Superannuation Board v Trade Practices Commission (1982) 150 CLR 282
questions.mnemonic: Finance isn't just banks and brokers, but super funds too
questions.answer:
(public) State Superannuation Board incorporated to make investments to develop a superannuation (retirement) fund
held: 'financial corporation' if deals in financial transactions even if corporation's purpose and general activities are directed towards some purpose other than the provision of financial services

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Fencott v Muller (1983) 150 CLR 304
questions.mnemonic: A [fun cot] for when the baby arrives
questions.answer:
company set up but has not actually done anything yet (a 'shelf' company)
held: should consider the purposes for which that company was set up (the intended activities), e.g. through the ‘constitution’ of the company (memorandum and articles of association)  
= ‘trading or financial corporation’

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Quickenden v O'Connor (2001) 109 FCR 243
questions.mnemonic: [Quick, in den] to the business of studying for uni exams
questions.answer:
university in question was a trading corporation because 28% of its income came from business activities (buying, selling and renting of property and investing, Festival of Perth, sale of publications and services, parking, provision of student accommodation etc.)
Note: Black CJ, and French J (obiter): ‘doubtful ... that [‘trading‘] extends to the provision of services under a statutory obligation to fix a fee determined by law and the liability for which, on the part of the student, appears to be statutory’

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: E v Australian Red Cross Society (1992) 27 FCR 310
questions.mnemonic: Red cross a charitable business
questions.answer:
Red Cross charity earned $2 million from sales = substantially engaging in trade (‘at kiosks, shops, street stalls or by direct sale of merchandise to the public’)
Hospital a trading corporation because $3.7 million of income came from business activities (i.e. selling things), 
relative to $12 million in State government funding, and $14 million in patient fees for medical services

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: R v Judges of the Australian Industrial Court; Ex parte CLM Holdings Pty Ltd (1977) 136 CLR 235
questions.mnemonic: No longer [holding] out like a shut [CLaM]
questions.answer:
upheld laws that created offences for ‘natural’ persons within a corporation
= allowed Commonwealth to target individual officers of a corporation with criminal and civil liability

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Actors and Announcers Equity Association v Fontana Films Pty Ltd (1982) 150 CLR 169
questions.mnemonic: Employees acting up [for tonna] money from clients
questions.answer:
provisions in the Commonwealth Trade Practices Act that prohibited 'secondary boycotts':  boycotting a business with which you have no dispute (e.g. main supplier of employer company) to put pressure on employer
held: valid because prohibited conduct that may cause harm to a trading or financial corporation i.e. not limited to laws with respect to the trading or financial activities of a corporation

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: NSW v Commonwealth (the Seas and Submerged Lands case) (1975) 135 CLR 337
questions.mnemonic: Submerged lands external to the land
questions.answer:
external affairs power could be used to make laws with respect to submerged lands along the Australian coastline
colonies had authority before federation
three majority judges held valid because territory that was ‘external’ to Australia
other majority judges held valid because it implemented a treaty

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Polyukhovic v The Commonwealth (the War Crimes Act case) (1991) 172 CLR 501
questions.mnemonic: [Pole you could've] wronged
questions.answer:
criminalized retrospectively war crimes committed in the WWII in Europe
held: valid because matters external to Australia
=not necessary for the Commonwealth law to concern Australia's relations with other countries
BUT… Brennan and Toohey JJ: may need to be a connection or a ‘nexus’ between the Commonwealth law and Australia (e.g. Australian citizen) = left this question open (as did Horta v The Commonwealth (1994) 181 CLR 183)

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: R v Burgess; Ex parte Henry (1936) 55 CLR 608
questions.mnemonic: [Burgers] should be closer to how they look in the ads
questions.answer:
regulations restricting aircraft behaviour at airports went significantly beyond that which Australia was obliged to implement under international law
Held:
(1) not only treaties enliven the external affairs power, can also be other sources of obligations, including recommendations of international bodies and even draft international conventions (depending on status in international law)
(2) to be valid, the domestic law needs to be in conformity with the international obligation

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Queensland v Commonwealth (the Daintree Rainforest Case) (1989) 167 CLR 232
questions.mnemonic: [Deign trea]ty to vest obligation
questions.answer:
Commonwealth empowered by Convention (i.e. treaty) to nominate areas of international significance requiring protection
Held: 
For the purposes of domestic (constitutional) law, whether an obligation exists is a matter of fact for the court to determine
Cth’s nomination of the Daintree could be taken as evidence that the Daintree had significance in the eyes of the international community
=obligations arose

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: R v Poole; Ex parte Henry (No. 2) (1939) 61 CLR 634
questions.mnemonic: Law must [pull] in the right direction
questions.answer:
Discrepancies existed between the domestic legislation and Convention with regard to airspace (the altitude at which aeroplanes could fly above airports)
held: certain discrepancies acceptable as long as legislation broadly giving effect to the obligations of the treaty: 
“the law must be ‘reasonably capable of being considered appropriate and adapted to implementing the treaty’”

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Horta v Commonwealth (1994) 181 CLR 183
questions.mnemonic: Unsucessfully ex[horted] High Court to invalidate treaty
questions.answer:
Jose Ramos Horta (later became PM and Pres) argued:
Indonesia's annexation of East Timor was illegal under international law
therefore Australia entering into a treaty with Indonesia with respect to this Timor Gap resources also illegal
therefore treaty could not be used to support domestic legislation through external affairs power
Held: not for the High Court to second-guess the validity of treaties under international law. It is for the Executive to enter into treaties (sign and ratify) and the Parliament to implement them through law
maybe a justiciability issue: a matter the courts will not rule upon, e.g. sovereignty

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Australian Communist Party v Commonwealth (1951) 83 CLR 1 (Communist Party Case)
questions.mnemonic: Reds under the bed just in your head
questions.answer:
Act dissolved Communist Party and allowed Governor General (on advice) to designate groups advocating communism and issue a control order over members restricting movement and association (and re individuals: restrictions on employment), where satisfied of threat
held: ‘recitals’ in Act or executive decision cannot make Act fit within defence power = invalid
objective proportionality test that allows court supervision: would a reasonable person consider the law appropriate and reasonable to achieve a defence purpose?

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Adelaide Company of  Jehovah 's Witnesses Incorporated v Commonwealth ("Jehovah 's Witnesses Case") (1943) 67 CLR 116
questions.mnemonic: [Dy'a have witness] to the crime? NO
questions.answer:
government declared Jehovah’s Witnesses a subversive organisation under regulations, raided premises
(1) aspect of the regulations that allowed the government to define ‘dangerous or unlawful doctrine’ invalid b/c not supported by defence power
(2) freedom of religion in s 116 is not absolute and must defer to legitimate defence concerns
South Australian Jehovah’s Witnesses pacifist group: religious beliefs included no participation in military service or any part in the ‘political affairs of the world’ (which in 1943, were deeply involved in war)
declared by Governor General (Cabinet) a subversive organisation under National Security (Subversive Associations) Regulations: impact on its rights and duties (e.g. property rights)
held: not infringed s116 (freedom to exercise religion balanced against the interests of the community, including the protection of social order)

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Thomas v Mowbray (2007) 233 CLR 307
questions.mnemonic: [To mass mow, bra]kes off: a terrorist uncontrolled against citizens
questions.answer:
regime imposing control orders on individuals for the purposes of “preventing a terrorist act” (here, Al Qua’ida trained ‘Jihad’ Jack)
Gleeson CJ, Gummow and Crennan JJ: internal threats fell within the ‘primary aspect’ of 51(vi)
To protect members of the public as members of the Commonwealth (Gleeson CJ and Gummow and Crennan JJ)
As a historical aspect of the protection of the realm from insurrection (Gummow and Crennan JJ)
The question of ‘war’ or ‘peace’ or ‘reasonable’ or ‘adapted’ wasn’t necessary since it was directly within the ambit of the primary aspect of the power (Gummow and Crennan JJ)
Kirby J (dissent): must be a threat to the body politic

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Ruddock v Vadarlis (The Tampa Case) (2001) 110 FCR 491
questions.mnemonic: Executive Minister Ruddock will [temper] expectations of boat people
questions.answer:
historical prerogatives subsumed into s 61, which is informed by historical prerogatives
eg expelling aliens
core executive powers (e.g. the defence prerogative) would require an explicit indication of parliamentary intent to displace
Commonwealth executive power is limited by the distribution of power among Commonwealth and States in the Constitution

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Burns v Ransley (1949) 79 CLR 101
questions.mnemonic: Treason once punished with [burns]
questions.answer:
Crimes Act offence of ‘inciting hatred of the sovereign... or the government... so as to endanger the Commonwealth’. 
Held: valid exercise of the incidental power to support the executive power of protecting the state and its institutions

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Victoria v The Commonwealth (‘the AAP Case’) (1975) 134 CLR 338
questions.mnemonic: Australian Assistance Plan gave birth to the nation(hood power)
questions.answer:
regional grants, which were ruled invalid
 (at least) within s 61 (executive power) and  ss 51 (xxxix) incidental legislative power, there is:
 a ‘capacity to engage in enterprises and activities peculiarly adapted to the government of a nation and which cannot otherwise be carried on for the benefit of the nation’ (Mason J)

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Matthews v The Chicory Marketing Board (Victoria) (1938) 60 CLR 263
questions.mnemonic: [Math use]ful for tax
questions.answer:
A tax is:(1) a compulsory exaction of money 
(2) by a public authority
(3) for public purposes 
(4) enforceable by law and 
(5) not a payment for services rendered

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Air Caledonie International v Commonwealth (1988) 165 CLR 462
questions.mnemonic: Can't get into the country with [car lead on ya] so have to pay reasonable cleaning fee
questions.answer:
Airlines collected ‘fee’ from all international airline passengers entering Australia for the Commonwealth to cover the costs of administration of immigration procedures 
Not public authority(?)
Not public purpose(?)
Held: tax rather than a fee for service
=Matthews a sufficient but not exhaustive definition of a tax
More likely to be a fee rather than a tax if:
the service is optional
there a discernible relationship between the fee and the services rendered, e.g. relationship between the amount of the fee and the value of the services provided or the costs involved in providing that service

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Australian Tape Manufactures Association Ltd v Commonwealth (1993) 176 CLR 480
questions.mnemonic: Nothing private if you get it on tape
questions.answer:
an exaction (collected by a private company) imposed upon sellers of blank tapes to compensate the music industry for music piracy = tax
private collecting body
= exaction by public authority can be delegated/indirect
While apparently in the interests of private parties, nevertheless acting for the public purpose of combating music piracy
=public purpose defined broadly

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Harper v Victoria (1966) 114 CLR 361
questions.mnemonic: Regulators always [harp]ing on about salmonella
questions.answer:
regulation of the egg industry such as testing, marking and stamping
held: activity could be regarded as a service and reasonable connection between the fee and the cost of providing these services 
=not a tax

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Parton v Milk Board (Vic) (1949) 80 CLR 229
questions.mnemonic: Tax [per ton] of milk not a fee
questions.answer:
fees imposed on the milk industry
held: not related to the services provided, rather funded administration and regulation of the industry generally (instead of a particular service) 
Held: a tax
followed in Swift v Boyd-Parkinson (1962) 108 CLR 189 (meat inspection)
consequences: State tax invalid as excise

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Northern Suburbs General Cemetery Reserve Trust v Commonwealth (1993) 176 CLR 555
questions.mnemonic: Shouldn't have to pay service fee for other employers working their staff into the grave
questions.answer:
Held: exaction of money from employers for workforce training a tax (not a service fee)
because no necessary connection between an individual person receiving a service and his or her obligation to pay (employees of a given employer might not receive any benefit at all)

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: General Practitioners Society of Australia v Commonwealth (1980) 145 CLR 532
questions.mnemonic: GPs provide and receive a service
questions.answer:
a statutory-mandated (compulsory) fee for licence to practise medicine = not tax
these generally have clear relationship between that fee and the service (i.e. the accurate assessment of eligibility and provision of the licence)
but if the fee was unreasonably large probably would not be a reasonable connection between the fee and that service

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Hematite Petroleum Pty Ltd v Victoria (1983) 1515 CLR 599
questions.mnemonic: [Him a tight petroleum] baron, let's gouge him with massive fee
questions.answer:
State imposed $10 million as a 'licence fee' to operate a pipeline transporting petroleum
in operation a tax on the petroleum itself
because no reasonable relationship between the service of assessing/providing that licence and the fee involved
Consequence: invalid excise under s 90 (see below) because a tax on a stage in the production of a good
$10 mill 'service fee' for licence fee to use pipe had no reasonable connection to cost or value of ‘service’: actually an excise because tax on a stage in the production of oil (in substance, even if not in form)

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Re Dymond (1959) 191 CLR 11
questions.mnemonic: [Diamond] can coexist with the rough
questions.answer:
taxing act and separate ‘assessment’ act, which included an additional exaction if non-payment of the liability imposed by the  taxing act
Held: penalty rather than a tax
=could therefore exist alongside the other non-taxing provisions of the assessment Act (see next slide)

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Permanent Trustee Australia Ltd v Commissioner of State Revenue (Victoria) (2004) 220 CLR 388
questions.mnemonic: [Permanent trust, Australia] can have in a fair tax system
questions.answer:
Commonwealth Places (Mirror Taxes Act) 1998 (Cth) applied surrounding State tax regimes to ‘Commonwealth places’ (e.g. a Cth military base within a State)
which could produce differences in liabilities in different States (because State taxation regimes had varying rates)
held: (1) the differential treatment and unequal outcomes here were the product of differences (in State law) that were ‘appropriate and adapted to a proper objective’ rather than a conscious attempt to give a preference
i.e. motive relevant, revealed by proportionality
(2)common practice to split incidental matters from the Act that actually imposes the taxation: 'taxing Act' and 'assessment Act’, but not necessary: ‘incidental’ provisions to a taxing Act related to such things as assessment, collection, and recovery may be mixed with taxing provisions"

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Conroy v Carter (1968) 118 CLR 90
questions.mnemonic: [Con Roy to cart a] different amount of tax
questions.answer:
Cth law allowed States to collect Commonwealth taxes, but the way States implemented this created a differential impact on people of different localities
Held: Commonwealth law must be read on its own terms (i.e. look at the provisions): =non-discriminatory

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Fortescue Metals Group Ltd v Commonwealth [2013] HCA 34
questions.mnemonic: State royalties [forte skew]ed against States, but their own doing
questions.answer:
Cth mining ‘super profits’ tax for earnings over $75 mill; Cth gave company (State) royalty credit, but without adjusting Cth amount, this would allow States to gain revenue at the expense of the Cth or even undermine the tax] so if company paid lower State royalties, must pay higher Cth tax 
Held: tax not discriminatory or preferential on its terms (discrimination resulted from State laws)

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Ha v NSW (1997) 189 CLR 465
questions.mnemonic: [Ha], time for a GST, States; no more excises
questions.answer:
NSW tried to circumvent s 90 by calculating the exaction ('franchise licence fee') based on prior production (the value of the tobacco sold in the previous month) 
Held: in substance a tax imposed on the production of a good (tobacco) = invalid
Note:  Ha led to creation of the Cth GST which is passed back to the States to replace lost revenue

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Attorney-General (Vic) (Ex rel Black) v Commonwealth (the DOGS case) (1981) 146 CLR 559
questions.mnemonic: Defence of Government Schools unsucessfully protesting basis for grants to non-secular, private schools
questions.answer:
(1) Commonwealth may make grants to a State for any purpose regardless of whether there is a corresponding Commonwealth head of power
(2) Freedom of religion does not exist with regard to State legislation
Constitutional convention debates: States were originally included in this provision but removed
Commonwealth using State grants power (s 96) on the condition that some money given to non-government (many religious) schools 
Held: Commonwealth may not set up a state religion (e.g. the Church of Australia), but…
s116 not created to ensure strict separation between church and state in Australia, rather to prevent the concession of special favours, titles, and advantages to one church denied to others
this financial support to religious schools was not ‘establishing a religion’: plaintiffs would have to show that special concessions or financial support amounted to establishing a religion
Murphy J (dissenting): consider what purposes achieved in practice from the support (i.e. endorsing/sponsoring religious teaching)

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Pye v Renshaw (1951) 84 CLR 58
questions.mnemonic: Commonwealth can't appropriate its [pie] and eat it too; [pay rents or] else
questions.answer:
(1)States not bound by requirements to grant just compensation for an acquisition (though usually do under State legislation)
(2)But Commonwealth cannot not use the grants power to circumvent the limitation in s 51(xxxi) (fair compensation when compulsorily acquiring land)
i.e. by giving State a smaller amount as inducement to acquire land without compensation

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: South Australia v Commonwealth (the First Uniform Tax case) (1941) 65 CLR 373
questions.mnemonic: I grant you that's a good defence
questions.answer:
Commonwealth strategy during the WWII of displacing the States from imposing income taxes:
imposed very high level of income tax, which meant heavy (unpopular) tax burden on workers if States maintained income tax
used expanded ‘wartime’ defence power (s 51(vi)) to give Commonwealth priority in tax collection and bankruptcy court proceedings
‘offered’ grants to the States on the condition that they not levy income taxes
Held: technically, a State could refuse the grant and impose its own income tax therefore valid grant

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Victoria v Commonwealth (the Second Uniform Tax case) (1957) 99 CLR 575
questions.mnemonic: No longer defensible, but grant anyway
questions.answer:
certain aspects of above laws (Cth priority) not supportable by ‘peacetime’ defence power, but grant still valid
Note: laws also survived 1947 Melbourne Corporation test

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Attorney-General for Victoria (Ex rel Dale) v The Commonwealth (the Pharmaceutical Benefits case) (1945) 71 CLR 237
questions.mnemonic: Keep close eye on drug spending
questions.answer:
a law appropriating money from the Consolidated Revenue Fund must stipulate the purpose and amount of that appropriation
Cf Combet v Cth (2005) 221 ALR 621, which upheld fairly vague link between specified purpose and political advertising

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Williams v The Commonwealth [2012] HCA 63
questions.mnemonic: William aka Bill, as in 'money bill'
questions.answer:
Funding agreement between Cth and school for chaplaincy services, unsupported by legislation
Executive power to spend and contract (as a legal person)?
Cth argued unlimited scope, or at least within what Cth could potentially legislate on in s 51, s 52, s 122, etc.
French CJ, Gummow, Crennan and Bell JJ: legislation is necessary to support the Executive’s contracting actions (and spending)
Heydon J (dissent): Cth executive power mirrors legislative power and contracting/spending does not need actual legislation
Note French CJ emphasised federalism (potential to circumvent Senate’s supervision of spending)
Cth Parliament immediately amended Financial Management and Accountability Act 1997 to give legislative support to various programs, but can they all be supported by Cth legislation?...
Williams v Commonwealth [2014] HCA 23 (Williams (No 2)): law passed to support agreement not supported by head of power

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: R v Kirby; Ex parte Boilermakers' Society of Australia (1956) 94 CLR 254
questions.mnemonic: Boilermakers welded judicial and executive power in the one court
questions.answer:
Commonwealth Court of Conciliation and Arbitration 
powers included:
executive powers: could conciliate and arbitrate industrial disputes and issue ‘awards’ (which created rights)
judicial powers: punish breaches of awards, which were established through this process of arbitration and conciliation
=applying/interpreting the law in authoritative/binding way
Held: impermissible mix of executive and judicial powers

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: R v Davison (1954) 90 CLR 353
questions.mnemonic: [Division] not permitted between judge and bankruptcy orders
questions.answer:
whether a non-judicial officer (Deputy Registrar of Bankruptcy) able to issue a voluntary  ‘order of sequestration’ to bankrupt person to distribute assets to creditors
debtor wanted not to be a valid bankrupt to avoid criminal offences e.g. trading while bankrupt
Registrar was attached to court but separate
Held:
Judicial power difficult to define
Voluntary orders not inherently judicial power
But historically both compulsory and voluntary sequestration orders were made by courts 
=impermissible exercise of  judicial power

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Precision Data Holdings Ltd v Wills (1991) 173 CLR 167
questions.mnemonic: No precision in defining tribunal vs court
questions.answer:
functions may be classified as either judicial or administrative according to the way in which they are exercised.' 
the context of the function
e.g. if performed by a tribunal, more likely to be non-judicial

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: R v Quinn (1977) 138 CLR 1
questions.mnemonic: [Queen] was historically a court too, but no longer
questions.answer:
whether (non-judicial) Registrar of Trademarks able to remove a trademark from the register
Held: 
historically, courts given power to remove trademarks from Register of Trademarks
but whether judicial power depends on nature of the effect on legal rights rather than historical contingency
whether a trademark was registered or not did not affect the existence of that right to the exclusive use of a trademark (registration is something different from ownership itself)
=not judicial power, therefore not impermissible

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Shell Company of Australia v the Federal Commissioner of Taxation (1930) 44 CLR 530
questions.mnemonic: A tribunal is only the [shell] of a court
questions.answer:
Privy Council listed some attributes a tribunal may permissibly have:
capacity to hear witnesses
act as an adjudicator between contending parties
express its opinion on points of law
but decisions relating to legal rights must be subject to review by a court (only court can make binding decisions and enforce them)

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Brandy v Human Rights and Equal Opportunity Commission (1995) 183 CLR 245
questions.mnemonic: HREOC trying to borrow the Court's [brand]
questions.answer:
Legislation effectively made the Federal Court endorse decisions (about disputes) made by the Human Rights Commission (which was not a Chapter III court)
If not appealed after 28 days effect as if it had been made by court
Held: ascertainment of existing rights by applying law to facts in a way that is enforceable is only open to a Chapter III court acting in its own right
Court cannot be used as a ‘rubber stamp’ decision to give bindingness to tribunal’s decision
=invalid vesting of judicial power in tribunal

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: AG v Breckler (1999) 197 CLR 83
questions.mnemonic: Super fund like a [brick layer] building wealth, but sometimes falls down needing arbitration
questions.answer:
Cth regime regulating superannuation (retirement) funds
registration not compulsory, but if registered:
fund received tax and other advantages 
and trustees agreed to comply with the regime 
including Tribunal decisions, which heard complaints against superannuation trustees (like managers of fund)
which a court could enforce
In this case, ‘deed’ setting up the fund in this case required registration
Tribunal not exercising judicial power because parties' rights were determined by private law (i.e. the trust deed), which required that that the trustee adhere to the regime, including Tribunal decisions
=effectively arbitrating according to terms in the deed (not judicial power that comes from sovereignty of the (public) state))
Unlike Brandy, Tribunal orders not enforceable on their own or automatically through some ‘rubber stamp’ registration process (court had discretion)

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: R v Trade Practices Tribunal; Ex parte Tasmanian Breweries (1970) 123 CLR 361
questions.mnemonic: Tribunal trouble brewing
questions.answer:
Trade Practices Tribunal empowered to make determination about trade practices ‘contrary to public interest’ upon application by a ‘commissioner’
Held: 
some 'adjudicative' functions that are nonetheless incidental to the administrative (executive) tasks that belong to the executive
these findings were not a binding declaration of existing rights and duties
=whether something ‘contrary to the public interest’ a matter of fact rather than law in this case

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: R v Spicer; Ex parte Australian Builders' Labourers Federation (1956) 100 CLR 277
questions.mnemonic: Courts should labour over law, not [spice] up policy
questions.answer:
court permitted by legislation to strike out rules of associations of employers or employees based on its opinion (discretion)
Held: criteria in legislation for this too vague and general; gave arbitrary discretion to the Commonwealth Industrial Court
amounted to impermissible 'policy' decisions based on consequences of decisions rather than legal rules and principles

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Cominos v Cominos (1972) 127 CLR 588
questions.mnemonic: Co offender/[co minors] held to a standard, albeit vague
questions.answer:
Courts often have discretionary powers in family law cases: 
e.g. custody disputes and maintenance exercised according to very vague criteria such as 'justice' or 'fairness'
Held: these are not completely arbitrary discretions because rather than taking general policy considerations into account, the discretions were to be applied to the individual specific case before the court

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Viro v R (1978) 141 CLR 88
questions.mnemonic: High Court and Privy Council no longer [vie over] cases
questions.answer: HCt declared no longer bound by PC decisions

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Chu Kheng Lim v Minister for Immigration (1992) 176 CLR 1
questions.mnemonic: [Chicken limb] food poisoned need quarantine, but not punishment
questions.answer:
‘non-punitive detention’
amendment to Migration Act prohibiting Court from releasing so-called 'designated persons' (specified asylum seekers)
Brennan, Dean, and Dawson JJ
determining criminal guilt and imprisonment an essentially judicial function, but exceptions:
detention of a suspect until charged (not punishment, supervised by the courts)
detention for harmful mental illness or infectious disease (not punishment)
Parliament's power to punish contempt (e.g. House punishing own member for not complying with order to submit documents, or citizen refusing to appear before Parliamentary committee) 
power of military tribunals, but note that a major debate has been whether military tribunals can hear all offences or just those with a 'service connection' The Australian Military Court was ruled unconstitutional in Lane v Morrison [2009] HCA 29 because it was exercising the judicial power of the Cth (beyond traditional military discipline) without the necessary attributes of a Chapter III court.
detention as an incident of the executive power of exclusion of non-citizens entering Australia
Gaudron J
Not exhaustive, might be more exceptions

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Grollo v Palmer (1995) 184 CLR 348
questions.mnemonic: [Growl over palm] to mask voice from wiretap
questions.answer:
Held: compatible with the judicial function for an ‘eligible judge’ (also ‘judge’ in Hilton v Wells) to issue phone tap warrant; test:
(1) whether consensual
(2) whether compatible with his or her position as a judge, i.e. 
(a) duration (temporary)
(b) degree of effect on capacity as a judge
(3) whether undermines public confidence in the judiciary
Note: not just for wire taps (persona designata generally)

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Wilson v Minister for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islanders Affairs (1996) 189 CLR 1
questions.mnemonic: Judge [will sign] report, but shouldn't
questions.answer:
Federal Court judge nominated to write a report under Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Heritage Protection Act 1984 (Cth)
Held: invalid, compromised judicial integrity and independence
Kirby J (dissenting)  Australian judges have traditionally been on Royal Commissions, which are similar (contextual approach, including historical practice)

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: North Australian Aboriginal Legal Aid Service v Bradley (2004) 218 CLR 146
questions.mnemonic: Judges employed [belatedly]
questions.answer:
‘acting judges’ ok at State/Territory level?
basic minimum requirements for a judge of any court, even at State/Territory level 
State judges not all required to have tenure but might be a point where too many acting judges would distort the character of the court
key question: whether reasonable person would think independence and impartiality of court compromised (no in this case)

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Kable v the Director of Public Prosecutions (NSW) (1996) 189 CLR 51
questions.mnemonic: Legislate hand [cable] ties for one potential offender? State your case
questions.answer:
‘preventative detention’: under Community Protection Act 1994 (NSW) NSW Sup Ct may order detention if reasonable grounds person likely to commit a serious act of violence
civil standard of proof 'on the balance of probabilities' rather than the criminal standard of 'beyond reasonable doubt‘
legislation specifically named one person: Gregory Kable
Held: invalid (4:2)
ss 71, 77 of Constitution allow State courts to be vested with federal jurisdiction= State courts must to a degree live up to expectations of federal courts (Chapter III courts)
Different judges emphasized different problems
Toohey J: decision about what might be done rather than what had been done (future crime)
Gaudron J: neither 'civil' ruling about existing rights and obligations nor a 'criminal' ruling regarding an offence against law
McHugh J: inconsistent with 'natural justice' / 'procedural fairness', the minimum standard of fairness that must be applied in the adjudication of a dispute, e.g. fair hearing to parties 
non criminal standard problematic
perception of independence as important as its actual independence: reasonable person might infer that court acting at the behest of the executive
Gummow J: cannot confer power to detain criminal without adjudication of criminal guilt

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Fardon v Attorney General (Qld) (2004) 223 CLR 575
questions.mnemonic: Too [far done], needs restraint
questions.answer:
Dangerous Prisoners Sexual Offenders Act 2003 (Qld) permitted reimprisonment of offenders (even if they haven't committed a new crime) if judge (on the application of AG) satisfied that on ‘cogent’ evidence there was a high degree of probability that a person would commit a serious sexual assault if released
majority narrowly limited possible applications of Kable
McHugh J: 
few limitations on State criminal law arrangements (cf Cth)
Kable should only be read to strike down legislation that singled out an individual for imprisonment beyond sentence in a way that threatens reputation of the court
Gummow J: judicial processes involved in securing the original conviction remedied the potentially problematic reimprisonment based on a non-judicial standard
criteria in the legislation for the court to consider, and high degree of independence from the legislature or executive in determining issues of fact, law and guilt
Callinan and Heydon JJ: Act not punitive and it allowed for judicial process including appellate review
Kirby J (dissent): punitive, therefore requires criminal standard and independent court and fair trial = invalid
In summary: new test (?), whether legislation was (as a whole) compatible with the 'institutional integrity' of a court

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Gypsy Jokers Motorcycle Club Inc v Commissioner of Police (2008) 234 CLR 532
questions.mnemonic: Bikies have to live like gypsys with house torn down
questions.answer:
legislation allowed Commissioner of Police (member of the executive branch) to issue a 'fortification warning notice' relating to a motorcycle clubhouse (a bikie hangout) if Commissioner has reasonable grounds for believing that the bikie hangout was armed
this notice affected an individual’s rights over the property
Act restricted review (appeal) to whether the Commissioner could reasonably have had the belief required to issue the notice, not whether issuing the notice was actually (objectively) reasonable
Held: valid, because subject to full review by court of ‘reasonable grounds’
Act allowed Commissioner to declare certain information secret (for the court’s use only, not the parties) ‘if its disclosure might prejudice the operations of the Commissioner’ 
Held (majority) did not impair the institutional integrity of the court because (as a matter of construction) the court was still able to be the final arbiter of whether information could actually prejudice the operations of the Commissioner

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: South Australia v Totani (2010) 271 ALR 662
questions.mnemonic: [Toe to knee] judge bows to executive
questions.answer:
Serious and Organised Crime (Control) Act 2008 (SA) allowed SA Attorney General to designate a ‘declared organisation’ based on AG’s satisfaction of a link between that organisation and crime
court must then impose a control order limiting a person's activities if it finds that person belongs to the declared organisation
Held: invalid
legislation impaired the actual and perceived independence of the court in matters going to the heart of the judicial functions such as personal freedom, criminal guilt, and punishment

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Wainohu v New South Wales [2011] HCA 24
questions.mnemonic: [Well I know who] is really in charge, the executive.
questions.answer:
Instead of AG, a judge of the NSW Supreme Court makes the designation of a ‘declared organisation’, which then triggers Supreme Court discretion to impose a control order
held: still invalid because the administrative designation was an integral component of the process of depriving a person of personal freedom, and was thus incompatible with the judicial function

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Asst Commissioner Michael James Condon v Pompano Pty Ltd [2013] HCA 7
questions.mnemonic: [Pomp ah no], closed court
questions.answer:
Police Commissioner applies to Court
Court may issue control orders, fortification removal orders etc if satisfied person:
(a) is, or has been, a member of a criminal organisation; and
(b) engages in, or has engaged in, serious criminal activity; and
(c) associates with any person for the purpose of engaging in, or conspiring to engage in, serious criminal activity
Held: valid, even though closed court (see below)Pompano alleged part of Gold Coast Finks bikie club
Criminal Organisation Act (Qld)
requires Court to hear an application that particular information is criminal intelligence without notice of the application being given to the person or organisation to which the information relates: s 66 
requires Supreme Court to exclude all persons other than those listed (in another section) from the hearing of an application for a declaration that particular information is criminal intelligence: s 70 
requires a closed hearing of any part of the hearing of the substantive application in which the court is to consider declared criminal intelligence (only specific persons may attend, not including defence): s 78
Held: as a whole, consistent with Chap III judicial power:
affidavits required details of what is alleged
the object of the Act relevant to means enacted to achieve it
not for reception of evidence that would otherwise be irrelevant or inadmissible; but actually allow for evidence which would otherwise not be adduced
criminal organisation public interest monitor as amicus curiae provides a degree of further protection
rules-based and inherent powers to ensure fairness, e.g. call witnesses of its own, could find an abuse of process

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Northern Territory v GPAO (1998) 196 CLR 553
questions.mnemonic: Good Procedure And Order in the NT family court followed
questions.answer:
Whether Family Court in NT bound by Territory procedural law because Judiciary Act states that court exercising federal jurisdiction in a State or Territory bound to apply the procedural laws of that State or Territory?
Held: Yes. NT Family Court was ‘obviously’ a federal court despite being in a Territory

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Nicholas v The Queen (1998) 193 CLR 173
questions.mnemonic: [Nick a lass], but she was undercover
questions.answer:
In wake of Ridgeway v The Queen (1995) 184 CLR 19 (drug trafficking evidence through undercover officers using entrapment Held: public policy, improper to admit)
amended legislation: ‘such evidence must not be ignored’, but ‘not intended to limit the discretion court has to exclude evidence in criminal proceedings’
held: valid
Brennan CJ: directions toward the proceedings but did not direct the outcome 
Majority distinguished Kable: not single out a specific person, class of people, or period of time, but was generally applicable
McHugh and Kirby JJ (in dissent): court's discretion over its procedures (for example, whether to exclude evidence) goes to the heart of the institutional integrity of the court

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Australian Building Construction Employees' and Builders Labourers' Federation v The Commonwealth (the BLF case) (1986) 161 CLR 88
questions.mnemonic: Builder's level not used in the unlevel courtroom
questions.answer: Commonwealth Parliament may modify rights and duties (even when a case is before the court), but may not interfere with the judicial process of a Chapter III court

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: International Finance Trust Co Ltd v New South Wales Crime Commissioner (the Criminal Assets Recovery Case) (2009) 240 CLR 319
questions.mnemonic: Legislature trying to steal assets of the court, namely independence over procedure
questions.answer:
legislation required 'ex parte' decisions on the application of the Crime Commissioner regarding retrieving proceeds of crime
French CJ: directing ex parte hearing a legislative usurpation of judicial power
Heydon J: one of the basics of judicial power in an adversarial judicial system is the importance of a hearing (allowing both parties an opportunity to put their case)

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Combet v Cth (2005) 221 ALR 621
questions.mnemonic: [Comb] through the budget accounts
questions.answer: Appropriations must be made by law though fairly vague link between specified purpose and political advertising

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Kingswell v R (1985) 159 CLR 264
questions.mnemonic: [Kings well] placed to decide severity of crime
questions.answer: The Commonwealth defines indictable offences for the purposes of the right to jury trial in s 80 of the Constitution;(affirmed by the majority in Cheng v R (2000) 203 CLR 248)

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Brownlee v R (2001) 207 CLR 278
questions.mnemonic: Mr [Brown lea]ves in shock, but the accused stays in the dock
questions.answer: A jury need not be constituted by 12 people – it may be constituted by as few as 10 if the others have been discharged as a result of illness –; and a jury need not be sequestered together

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Street v Qld Bar Association (1989) 168 CLR 461
questions.mnemonic: Shouldn't matter which [street] you live in to practise law
questions.answer:
Queensland Bar Association requirement that a legal practitioner must declare that they will “practice principally in Queensland” 
Held: disadvantage to Street because of NSW residency (would effectively have to give up NSW practice)
Limits?
Barwick CJ - laws critical to the operation of Government (eg voting)
McHugh J – laws that were entirely a matter for the residents and the Government (eg voting and qualifications for public office)
Mason J – rights for the enjoyment of State residents would fall outside section 117 (eg entitlement to State welfare benefits)

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Kruger v the Commonwealth (Stolen Generations case) (1997) 190 CLR 1
questions.mnemonic: [Crew go]ne, and incidentally religion too
questions.answer:
1918 Northern Territory ordinance made under Northern Territory Administration Act (Cth law under s 122 territories power) had authorised the breaking up of Aboriginal families (and thus religion)
Dawson and McHugh JJ: territories power was not limited by s 116, despite recent trend to interpret territories power in the context of the rest of the Constitution; but…
4 judges in obiter dicta seemed open to the possibility that freedom of religion extends to the territories power, but
Gummow J: rights and duties affected by the law did not indicate anything that proscribed or regulated conduct of a religious nature. 
Brennan CJ, Toohey J: not a law ‘for the prohibiting the free exercise of any religion’ (the effect on religion was incidental rather than the purpose of the law) 
Gaudron J: (open to the plaintiff’s argument) necessary to consider the extent to which a law operates to prevent the free exercise of religion: absence of strong social justification or disproportionality may indicate purpose to prevent community practices (including religion)

questions.question: Gillespie
questions.mnemonic: For David Gillespie, Australia Post is pesky

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: The Church of the New Faith v Commissioner for Pay-roll Tax (Vic) (the Scientology case) (1983) 154 CLR 120
questions.mnemonic: Scientology not a science
questions.answer:
Mason ACJ and Brennan J: necessary to adopt a flexible definition of religion given the multiplicity of religions in the world that do not necessarily conform to a Western idea of religion and God, but not a completely subjective test:
(1) belief in a supernatural being, thing, or principle
(2) acceptance of canons of conduct in order to give effect to that belief
Wilson and Deane JJ: indicia that suggest something is a ‘religion’
(1) a belief in the supernatural
(2) the ideas associated with the religion relate to man’s nature and place in the universe
(3) the ideas of the religion require or encourage observance of rituals or a code of conduct
(4) possibility of identifying a group adhering to those religious beliefs
(5) necessity for the believers themselves to identify what they are doing as a religion.
Murphy J: simply whether a group claims to be a religious group, conceding that some claims could be facetious or a hoax
Held: Scientology is a religion

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Nelson v Fish (1990) 92 ALR 187
questions.mnemonic: [Kneel son, fish] is the symbol of Christ
questions.answer:
some religions in effect excluded from undertaking recognised marriage ceremonies under the Marriage Act (government list of recognised religions and denominations) 
held: valid (provision in the Act permitting celebrants to conduct marriage ceremonies cured the potential defect in the law)

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Davis v the Commonwealth (1988) 166 CLR 79
questions.mnemonic: [Day vis] nationhood is protested against
questions.answer:
Australian Bicentennial Authority Act (Cth) gave Commonwealth exclusive use of certain symbols and trademarks relating to the bicentenary of white settlement
Aboriginal plaintiffs (incl Lou Davis) prevented from marketing T-shirts using trademark '200 years' to protest white invasion (liable to $2000 penalty)
Mason J: as a matter of characterisation, s 61 executive and incidental power might have supported the law, but not (as a purpose power) 'reasonably and appropriately adapted' to the purpose because disproportionate restriction on freedom of expression

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Australian Capital Television v Cth (1992) 177 CLR 106
questions.mnemonic: Can't keep political ads off TV
questions.answer:
Broadcasting Act (Cth) regulated political advertising
banned political advertising during an election period, with some exceptions to cover news or commentary
required television broadcasters to give some free advertising time to political parties during election period proportionate to current level of representation in the Parliament
held: regime invalid
Majority: implied right to political communication based on text, structure, or concepts underpinning the Constitution relating to representative government
Dawson J (dissent): Constitution's drafters left such matters to the Parliament to regulate in its wisdom, which is why Australia did not adopt a Bill of Rights; anyway, purpose of regime actually to protect elections against money politics

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Nationwide News v Wills (1992) 177 CLR 1
questions.mnemonic: [Nationwide], say what you [will] about government
questions.answer:
Cth legislation protected reputation of the Australian Industrial Relations Commission by making it an offence to insult the Commission
no defences such as fair comment or mistake of fact
journalist in appellant’s newspaper accused the Commission of corruption and was charged 
Brennan, Deane, Toohey, Gaudron JJ: invalid because of implied freedom of political communication that arises from the system of representative government enshrined in the Constitution
Mason CJ, and Dawson and McHugh JJ: invalid because not sufficiently connected to the conciliation and arbitration power

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Theophanous v Herald and Weekly Times (1994) 182 CLR 104
questions.mnemonic: ['They' often 'us'] when it comes to immigration, especially when minister in same community
questions.answer:
Member of Parliament (Theophanus, senior ALP MP involved with immigration committees) brought case of defamation against the defendant newspaper, which had published Ruxton letter accusing of bias to Greek migrants etc.; 
Mason CJ, Toohey and Gaudron JJ: 
implied right to political communication to publish material relating to government and political matters and members of Parliament in a way that relates to their performance as members of Parliament or suitability as members of Parliament
where this is present, no claim of defamation where:
defendant was unaware of the falsity of the material or not reckless as to its falsity
publication was reasonable in the circumstances
= i.e. don’t need to prove truth of the statement
= Paper able to rely on this defence= Theophanus lost
Deane J: maybe not even necessary for a defendant to prove the above (but changed mind in Stephens v West Australian Newspapers (1994) 182 CLR 211)

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Langer v the Commonwealth (1996) 186 CLR 302
questions.mnemonic: [Lang]uishing in jail for protesting election
questions.answer:
Electoral Act offence to encourage people to vote in a way other than the way prescribed in another section of the Act (full preferential voting: every box numbered in sequential order of preference)
But another section provided that if a voter did not stick to these rules precisely then the vote could still count (a 'saving' provision)
Langer encouraged others to vote '1' for first preference and '2' for every other candidate, which would defeat the purpose of preferences (to the detriment of big parties)
Majority: Cth has power to stipulate method of voting under s 24 (house of reps), s 31 (electoral system), and s 51(xxxvi) (provisional measures)
punitive enforcement provision a reasonably appropriate and adapted (proportionate) means to securing this end, thus only incidental interference with implied freedom of political communication
obiter: limitation on the freedom of the plaintiff to criticise the electoral system would be disproportionate
Gummow J: law designed to give substance to the system of representative democracy in the Constitution, not weaken it
Dawson J: (dissent) s 24 requires genuine choice; ss 31, 51(xxxvi) are purposive powers, disproportionate to that purpose because law in effect restricts provision of information to voters about voting (therefore not merely incidental interference with political communication)

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Lange v Australian Broadcasting Corporation (1997) 189 CLR 520
questions.mnemonic: [Long he] pursued the ABC, no defence directly
questions.answer:
[pr. Long-ee]
defamation case brought by a New Zealand politician against the ABC
(applying ACTV) freedom of communication on matters of government and politics (not only in election periods) to exercise a free and informed choice is an indispensable part of representative government created by the text of the Constitution, e.g. 'directly chosen by the people’; but…
(overruling Theophanous) not an individual ‘right’ to political expression like American Bill of Rights that can be invoked directly as a defence against defamation suit
Instead, creates an ‘area of immunity’ from Cth and State control and thus limits the capacity of the Cth or States to shape the common law (note: statute trumps common law)
'qualified privilege’: special common law defence to defamation because public interest, which now therefore includes entrenched minimum of certain political expression required by the Constitution

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Levy v Victoria (1997) 189 CLR 579
questions.mnemonic: Even protesters' [Levi] jeans won't stop hunter's bullets
questions.answer:
Victorian regulations prevented (by penalty) persons without a license from entering the area for duck hunting
Held: actions, such as entering a hunting area to protest against hunting could constitute political communication
but the law was proportionate ('reasonably appropriate and adapted') to the legitimate purpose of protecting the safety of the public

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Coleman v Power (2004) 220 CLR 1
questions.mnemonic: [Cold man in power] (police) should be impervious to insults
questions.answer:
Vagrants Act (Qld) created offence to use any threatening, abusive, or insulting words to any person or to behave in an insulting manner
Coleman (mildly) insulted a police officer and convicted
Test:
First, does the law effectively burden freedom of communication about government or political matters in terms, operation, or effect? [implied in Lange test?]
Second, is the law reasonably appropriate and adapted to serve a legitimate end in a way that is compatible with the maintenance of representative government?’ [both limbs of Lange test]
Majority: Burden, but keeping public places free from violence a legitimate end and law proportionate if read down to (Gummow and Hayne JJ): 'insulting words or behaviour' that are 'fighting words' likely to provoke a physical response
=conviction quashed on the facts
Political content?
Kirby J: political discussion need not be civil
Gleeson CJ, Callinan J, Heydon J (dissenting): must have some limits on definition of ‘political’ speech; public order a legitimate policy goal

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: McCloy v New South Wales (2015) 89 ALJR 857
questions.mnemonic: Political donations [may cloy] government
questions.answer:
NSW’s Election Funding, Expenditure and Disclosures Act provided for caps on political donations; banned certain indirect campaign contributions, and making or accepting political donations by certain persons, including property developers
French CJ, Kiefel, Bell and Keane JJ: determining whether a law is reasonably appropriate and adapted to advance a legitimate object:
 A law must be:
(1) suitable, as having a rational connection to the object; 
(2) necessary, in the sense of there being no obvious and compelling, reasonably available and less restrictive alternative; and 
(3) adequate in its balance, having regard to the importance of the legislative purpose and the extent of the restriction.
Held: valid b/c rationally connected with the legitimate purpose of preventing corruption and undue influence in government affairs. 
ban on donations from property developers reflected the potentially higher risk of corruption in planning decisions. 
the less restrictive alternative measures proposed by the plaintiffs could not be said to be equally effective and would undoubtedly reduce the efficacy of the statutory scheme 
extent of the restrictions was more than balanced by the benefits sought to be achieved

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: R v Smithers (1912) 16 CLR 99
questions.mnemonic: Attempt to [smother] free movement of criminals
questions.answer:
New South Wales law attempted to restrict entry into the State of persons who had been convicted and sentenced to imprisonment of more than one year
Barton J: States may be entitled to limit travel across borders for certain reasons relating to health and safety, but otherwise free s 92 'intercourse' includes guaranteed access the institutions of the national government
Upheld in Gratwick v Johnson (1945) and Cole v Whitfield (1988): relatively strong restriction upon the States

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Cunliffe v the Commonwealth (1994) 182 CLR 272
questions.mnemonic: [Can't live] here if you can't get a registered immigration lawyer
questions.answer:
Cth law required registration of lawyers to provide legal services to migrants
plaintiffs argued this placed restrictions on communications that could prevent interstate intercourse, e.g. phone calls on a migrant's behalf to a government official in another State
Held: permissible restriction
despite the term 'absolutely free' there is no absolute protection upon trade, commerce and intercourse between the States
If legitimate end, a limitation on trade, commerce and intercourse may be found to be incidental (a mere side effect) of that law
McHugh J: proportionality test for incidental restrictions on trade and commerce between States, legitimate aim of regulating industry to protect migrants

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: AMS v AIF (1999) 199 CLR 610
questions.mnemonic: A Mother Stuck
questions.answer:
Cth law gave Family Court power to prevent a parent from relocating with his or her child if need to maintain a relationship between that child and other parent
Held: merely incidental and proportionate to a valid law with a legitimate end

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Cole v Whitfield (1988) 165 CLR 360
questions.mnemonic: [Coal and wheat field]s are national commodities, lobsters are not and need local protection
questions.answer:
Tasmanian regulations specifying a minimum size for catching and selling crayfish
in effect, out-of-State fishermen could not sell in Tasmania their elsewhere legally caught small crayfish
held: Neither in terms nor effect were the regulations aimed at protectionism (i.e. a competitive advantage to local trade in Tasmania) and instead were designed to conserve crayfish
earlier cases (before 1988) had focused on the terms of a law (formalist approach), or on individual right to sell goods, or different limbs of discrimination
new test (wiping the slate clean): 
Terms or effect: 'The concept of discrimination necessarily embraces factual discrimination as well as legal operation. A law will discriminate against interstate trade or commerce if the law on its face subjects that trade or commerce to a disability or disadvantage or if the factual operation of law produces such a result.’
+Protectionist purpose makes the discrimination invalid

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Bath v Alston Holdings (1988) 165 CLR 411
