questions.mnemonic: [Bar the ol' stone]r who brings weed from interstate
questions.answer:
tobacco retailers licence fee in Victoria calculated progressively higher for amounts of out-of-state tobacco sold
Ostensibly to offset Victorian licence fee on Victorian wholesalers
Held: discriminatory in a protectionist sense
Majority: disincentive for retailers to buy out-of-state tobacco = discriminatory in a protectionist sense
Dissenters: no discriminatory protectionist effect when scheme was viewed as a whole 
Victorian wholesalers would pass licence fee cost on to retailers, which would offset any advantage to retailers in buying local product
seems more consistent with Cole v Whitfield?

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Barley Marketing Board (New South Wales) v Norman (1990) 171 CLR 182
questions.mnemonic: [No man] can sell barley except through us
questions.answer:
Malting barley used for beer etc.
Only centralised NSW Barley Marketing Board permitted to market and sell barley in NSW 
=local barley growers could no longer sell in another state because contracts void
Under pre-Cole v Whitfield test probably invalid because individual right in section 92 to trade within Australia
Post-Cole v Whitfield: focus on the possible protectionist terms or effect of the law, rather than the perspective of the individual trader: any disadvantage or greater burden to interstate trade?
Held: even if State growers could no longer sell their produce in other States, this did not have a prejudicial effect against commercial interests in other States (e.g. no demonstrated restriction of supply beyond NSW that would then give commercial advantage to NSW industry) 
= valid

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Castlemaine Tooheys v South Australia (1990) 169 CLR 436
questions.mnemonic: [Castle men to ease] burden on local brewers
questions.answer:
South Australian regulations mandating retail customer refund of 15 cents for returned standard (non-refillable) bottle and 4 cents for eco (refillable) bottle = eco bottles more profitable for retailers
Also required that beer suppliers from out-of-state make own arrangements for reclaiming returned bottles (SA Gov arranged for return to local suppliers)
=competitive advantage for local producers in the South Australia market (SA had more eco bottles)
Held: effect of the law discriminatory in a protectionist sense
test of proportionality and reasonableness to distinguish Cole v Whitfield: South Australia could have achieved same environmental goals by some other less protectionist/discriminatory means 
SA acknowledged that a smaller differential than 4c/15c would have achieved the desired goals of reducing litter and production fuels
South Australia’s disproportionate chosen means suggested purpose of discriminatory burden upon interstate trade

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Betfair v Western Australia (2008) 234 CLR 318
questions.mnemonic: [Bet fairly], whatever WA says about the consequences
questions.answer:
Betfair (world's largest Internet betting exchange) taking bets beyond the State on WA horse races
WA Parliament made betting on Internet sites illegal and created a system of licences to bet on WA races
argued betting industry essential to State revenue/welfare and racing a cultural institution needing protection from corrupting Internet gambling
Held: invalid
mere protection of revenue cannot justify discrimination against interstate trade and insufficient data to suggest  other social, economic, or cultural importance of local betting industry indicates a non-protectionist purpose
even if objectives of the Act were apparently legitimate, the means by which that objective is achieved must be 'reasonably appropriate and adapted' (proportionate) to that object, else they indicate purpose of discrimination in a protectionist sense (as in this case through criminalisation)

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Betfair Pty Limited v Racing New South Wales [2012] HCA 12
questions.mnemonic: NSW treated Betfair [fairly] just like everyone else
questions.answer:
License fee for use of NSW Racing info
Imposed uniformly but progressively higher based on turnover
=large effect on Betfair as the biggest trader
Held: s 92 doesn’t protect individual traders. Not protectionist in law or operation.

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Wurridjal v Commonwealth (2009) 237 CLR 309
questions.mnemonic: [Would y'all leave us alone to enjoy our land?]
questions.answer:
Exercise of territories power (s 122) territories probably is bound by compensation guarantee despite Teori Tau v Commonwealth (1969) 119 CLR 564; Commonwealth acquired five-year leases of townships over Aboriginal lands for “national emergency response” to abuse of Indigenous children in NT (attached conditions of use)
Held: French CJ: even acquisition of purely statutory rights for a ‘regulatory’ purpose may be subject to s 51(xxxi)
Depends on nature of rights (here, Aboriginal Land Rights Act was precisely to give rights equivalent to common law ‘fee simple’ property rights)
But Emergency Response Act did not ’diminish the measure of the entitlement’ conferred on the plaintiffs by the Aboriginal Land Rights (Northern Territory) Act

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: P J Magennis Pty Ltd v Commonwealth (1949) 80 CLR 382
questions.mnemonic: [My genesis] is in another power
questions.answer:
s51(xxxi) works with other powers: acquisition must be authorised by another head of power (e.g. corporations power, core or incidental)
Protection extends to other powers: other heads of power bound by compensation guarantee

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Commonwealth v Western Australia (1999) 196 CLR 392 (‘the Mining Act Case’)
questions.mnemonic: Bundles of property taken from the mines
questions.answer:
‘Property’ is a bundle of rights: can be divided up and attributed to different people (e.g. landlord-owner, tenant, bank, easement)
Each right susceptible to acquisition

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Minister of State for the Army v Dalziel (1944) 68 CLR 261
questions.mnemonic: A good [deal] depends on the circumstances (Scottish pron), including defence purpose and right to profit
questions.answer:
pronounced 'dee-all'; (1)Commonwealth acquired land for defence purposes from tenant of land who operated a car park in New South Wales 
Held: ‘property’ includes real property and personal property (including intellectual property)
but also ‘incorporeal hereditaments’ (right to receive rent or make a profit from a thing) and ‘chose in action’ (e.g. claim for damages)
(2) whether a defence purpose impacts upon question of reasonable compensation in the circumstances

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Telstra Corporation Limited v The Commonwealth (2008) 234 CLR 210
questions.mnemonic: [Tell straight] to the phone company: you must share network
questions.answer:
Commonwealth law for 3rd party access to the Telstra phone network through a system of licences
Held: 
Not an acquisition 
Until late 1990s Telstra was a government-owned enterprise
As part of privatisation deal, the government ensured that Telstra's competitors could have access to the network
Therefore Telstra never really ‘owned’ the network but operating the network with permission of the Government through legislation
Parliament could just as easily revoke/modify that permission without compensation

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Georgiadis v Australian and Overseas Telecommunications Corporation(1994) 179 CLR 297
questions.mnemonic: [George, are these] really yours?
questions.answer:
(1)Property rights that are not based on the ‘general law’ (e.g. of property) but are instead created and conferred by specific statutes are inherently susceptible to variation (less likely to be an acquisition)
= workers' compensation payments extinguished rather than acquired
(2) Plaintiff deprived of right to sue Cth for injury: acquisition because ‘benefit’ to Cth of being released from liability

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Health Insurance Commission v Peverill (1994) 179 CLR 226
questions.mnemonic: [Pay have, or ill] patients says doctor, but no remedy
questions.answer:
remuneration paid to a doctor based on a schedule of fees in legislation, which Parliament changed (reduced) retrospectively
held: not an acquisition but rather a genuine ‘adjustment’ of competing claims, rights and obligations in the common interest between parties within a statutory context

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Mutual Pools and Staff Pty Ltd v Commonwealth (1994) 179 CLR 155
questions.mnemonic: Tax is a [mutual pool] of funds and not property
questions.answer:
Commonwealth deprived company of right to a refund under agreement with ATO made pending litigation regarding validity of tax
held: (1) merely a ‘genuine adjustment’ of interests within a statutory context (the taxation scheme);
 Some things are exceptions to acquisition: e.g. tax, forfeiture for crime
(2) ‘acquisition’ not necessarily physically taking possession of, but must be something more than the Commonwealth merely ‘affecting’ enjoyment of your property rights (regulation of use)
(3) ‘acquisition’ involves benefit to the Commonwealth (e.g. not having to pay a debt in this case, but still not an acquisition)

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Nintendo v Centronics (1994) 181 CLR 134
questions.mnemonic: Parents can confiscate kid's Nintendo Playstation any time
questions.answer:
Centronics had been profiting from importing and selling game machines, but this ended when new legislation allowed Nintendo to enforce its intellectual property rights over certain silicon chip layouts
Held: 
Context: statutory scheme for the protection of intellectual property rights under the s 51(xviii)
In this context and in light of the intent behind s 51(xviii), conferral of intellectual property rights and resulting limitation of proprietary rights of others is not an acquisition = mere ‘adjustment of rights’

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Commonwealth v WMC Resources (1998) 194 CLR 1
questions.mnemonic: With Minor Change to exploration permit
questions.answer:
Commonwealth legislation reduced the area of an exploration permit held by a mining company
Held: not an acquisition; Gummow J:
test is whether a property right has been acquired vs whether the content of that right has been merely reduced or affected in some way
But statutory origin is not determinative (cf Giorgiadis)

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Attorney-General for the Northern Territory v Chaffey (2007) 231 CLR 651
questions.mnemonic: Subsisting property rights no mere [chaff], even if statutory
questions.answer:
Northern Territory legislation retrospectively exempted superannuation from compensation scheme for injured workers
Held: not an acquisition
But obiter dicta: right created by statute is not necessarily immune to the just compensation guarantee
Key feature of WMC was that mining licences subject to periodic adjustment (in legislation)
But subsisting statutory exclusive rights such as those of copyright and patent owners might be protected by just compensation guarantee (cf Centronics)

Held: might have been, but no benefit to the Cth

questions.question: Mamarika v The Queen (1982) 42 ALR 94
questions.mnemonic: [Mama, eek! A] spear in my leg

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Mabo v Queensland (No 2) ("Mabo case") (1992) 175 CLR 1
questions.mnemonic: [My boy]s were here first
questions.answer:
Held: Indigenous property rights (native title) survived white colonisation of Australia
questioned the concept of terra nullius ('empty land')
sovereign acquisition of territory under 18th century international law:
conquest: local law continues until expressly overridden
cession through treaty: local law continues until expressly overridden
settlement of uninhabited land: law travels with settlors
inhabited land? 18th century European definition related to agricultural development of land, Aborigines tended to hunt rather than cultivate land
historical data proving that Indigenous communities had sophisticated social structures and law
= Australia inhabited so local law (native title) capable of surviving British acquisition of sovereignty (until overridden by law or impliedly through inconsistent disposition of land)
did not overrule Coe v Commonwealth (1979) 24 ALR 118 which rejected any survival of indigenous sovereignty after British colonisation of Australia
= probably little scope for common law to recognise Indigenous sovereignty in any part of Australia
Vague about whether Australia ‘conquered’

questions.question: Western Australia v Commonwealth (Native Title Act Case) (1995) 183 CLR 373
questions.mnemonic: Australian natives' excluded from race power until '67

Native Title Act a law 'with respect to' race = valid under s 51(xxvi)
Up to court to decide whether a law is really ‘necessary’

questions.question: Kartinyeri v Commonwealth (Hindmarsh Island Bridge Case) (1998) 195 CLR 337

heritage legislation amended to allow building of Hindmarsh Island Bridge

(dismissing the claim) Court evenly divided regarding whether race power can be used to enact laws that disadvantage Aboriginal people

questions.tags: Australian constitutional law, Australian case law, Australian law
questions.question: Hogan v Hinch [2011] HCA 4
questions.mnemonic: [Hogging every inch] of the limelight so want open court
questions.answer: Hinch argued that a suppression order power on the part of the courts distorted their institutional integrity and also it is contrary to an implication in Chapter III of the Constitution that courts should be open. The Court specified that the issue at hand was whether the Victorian Parliament could confer this power on the Victorian Court. It held that Chapter III allows courts power incidental to the exercise of judicial power. This explains why there are examples in the Federal Court and family law and established exceptions relating to privacy and trade secrets that allow courts to restrict publication of evidence and conduct proceedings in private regardless of section 17 of the Federal Court act that requires an open court in principle. The consequences are that first, there is no absolute limit on the legislative power from Chapter III; second, a law such as this is valid and does not deny an essential characteristic of a court exercising federal jurisdiction; and third, because of this it is not an attack on institutional integrity of the court as independent and impartial
